le. Moral Nation traces the instrumental role of ideologies about narcotics in the country's efforts to reestablish its legitimacy as a nation and empire.As Kingsberg demonstrates, Japan's growing status as an Asian power and a "moral nation" expanded the notion of "civilization" from an exclusively Western value to a universal one. Scholars and students of Japanese history, Asian studies, world history, and global studies will gain an in-depth understanding of how Japan's experience with narcotics influenced global standards for sovereignty and shifted the aim of nation building, making it no longer a strictly political activity but also a moral obligation to society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDrug abusexSocial aspectszJapanxHistory. 0aDrug trafficzJapanxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  a19th century japanese history.  a20th century japanese history.  aaddiction.  aasia.  aasian power.  aasian studies.  abureaucrats.  acivic.  acivilization.  acrusades against opium.  adoctors.  adrug use.  aempire.  aglobal history.  ahistory of narcotics.  ainternational relations.  ainterwar period.  ajapan.  ajapanese history.  alaw enforcement.  alocal studies global themes series.  amedical.  amedicine.  amodern history.  amodern japan.  amoral obligation.  anarcotics.  anation building.  aopium.  apolitical activity.  apolitical.  ascientists.  aself rule.  asovereignty.  aworld history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027673440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095748040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97805209574804